{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"81e0ac87-64a1-456d-88f9-2621a85e21c8","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `MauiProgram.cs` (or your app builder setup) via `ConfigureLifecycleEvents`:\n\n```csharp\nusing Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;\n\nbuilder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n{\n#if ANDROID\n    events.AddAndroid(android => android\n        .OnPause(activity => { /* your code */ })\n        .OnStop(activity => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n    events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n        .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* your code */ }));\n#endif\n});\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code conditional.\n- `AddAndroid` gives access to `OnCreate`, `OnStart`, `OnResume`, `OnPause`, `OnStop`, `OnDestroy`, etc.\n- `AddiOS` gives access to `DidEnterBackground`, `WillEnterForeground`, `WillTerminate`, `OnActivated`, etc.\n- Add the `Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents` namespace.\n\nThis approach avoids custom platform renderers or subclassing platform `Activity`/`AppDelegate`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"dfaab94c-ba45-427a-b6ec-9f8a3c9f1753","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development. I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":387,"requestId":"3C3F:3F94EE:D91335:10D1B6D:6A012985"},"id":"6e147750-831f-426e-8292-29c74054b297","timestamp":"2026-05-11T00:57:49.373Z","parentId":"19b1f59d-20e2-4092-b5c2-2c46a5ccb6a8"}
